actions/get_or_create_user.py.message:
So you can just except CalledProcessError here (no need to store it in a temp variable) instead of deleting the variable. This is quite confusing and only used to work around a linting error and you can just avoid it in a pythonic way with:

try:
    ... do something
except CalledProcessError:
    pass

I do think it would be better to also leave a debug log statement indicating that the attempt to get the authentication failed. You probably want to check the return code (ceph returns standard linux errno values). I believe that auth get will return an ENOENT when the user doesn't exist, but what happens if the local credentials don't allow for it? You'll get an EACCES. I think for this code, it's fine to just leave a log message and try down below - but the log message should be included so when a bug report comes in we know what succeeded or failed.

